    Andryan VT December 4, 2015 at 4:14 am #

    Hello Adrian, I‚Äôm currently implementing your motion detection into my system ( I used the part 2 one) and I want to cite the technique to my paper. Is there any formal paper to cite on or books? Cause citing from website isn‚Äôt permitted from my uni. Based on what I‚Äôm reading, you are not implementing Improved Gaussian Mixture and that 2 paper above in the motion detection right? Thank you in advance (I‚Äôm already posting this comment in the part 1 section)
    Reply
        Adrian Rosebrock December 4, 2015 at 6:24 am #

        Hey Andryan, you are correct, I am not using a GMM based method or anything advanced. It‚Äôs simply keeping track of the past N frames and performing a subtraction. There is a well known and extremely simple method for background subtraction so there I‚Äôm not even sure what the ‚Äúoriginal‚Äù paper was that used this (if there even was one).
        Reply
            Andryan VT December 5, 2015 at 2:20 am #

            Thanks for your reply. I will try finding the paper for it haha ! Btw, does a GMM based method too much for Raspberry Pi?
            Reply
                Adrian Rosebrock December 5, 2015 at 6:21 am #

                If you‚Äôre using the Pi 2, you might be able to use the GMM method. If you don‚Äôt perform shadow detection that will also help speed things up. But in reality, I wouldn‚Äôt expect to get any more than a few frames per second performance.
                Reply
    Peter Grove December 5, 2015 at 3:19 pm #

    I am trying to detect when the evening/night prevents a good image so that. Can you please give me a pointer as to a simple calculation I can do on the frame to see if evening has come.

    Thanks
    Reply
        Adrian Rosebrock December 6, 2015 at 7:18 am #

        If you keep track of the past N frames (where N would likely have to contain 15-30 minutes worth of frames), you could compute their average over few minutes. Once the average falls below a preset threshold (meaning the average is getting ‚Äúdarker‚Äù, you can say that night has come.
        Reply
