    halfcoder February 7, 2016 at 1:30 am #

    will this project work with opencv 3.0 and is there any need for wifi adapter in this project??
    Reply
        Adrian Rosebrock February 8, 2016 at 3:51 pm #

        If you do not want to upload the images to Dropbox, then you do not need a WiFi adapter or an ethernet connection for this project. Simply comment out the code related to uploading to Dropbox.

        As for the code working with OpenCV 3, all you need to do is change the cv2.findContours call to:

        (_, cnts, _) = cv2.findContours(thresh.copy(), cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)

        You can read more about the change to cv2.findContours between OpenCV 2.4 and OpenCV 3 in this post .
        Reply
    Miraj February 10, 2016 at 9:25 am #

    Awesome post Adrian, got everything working.

    I was wondering what‚Äôs the advantage of this method of background subtraction vs. the one outlined on the OpenCV site (here: http://docs.opencv.org/master/db/d5c/tutorial_py_bg_subtraction.html#gsc.tab=0 )

    I understand Median Blur is slightly computationally intensive, but removes speckles. I was more asking what the advantages are around using the BackgroundSubtractor functions available already and periodically calling those?

    I‚Äôm essentially looking for a way to determine a way to determine the background of a frame if there is existing movement throughout the video (such as people walking around and/or sitting down).

    Thanks a bunch.
    Reply
        Adrian Rosebrock February 10, 2016 at 4:32 pm #

        OpenCV does indeed have built-in methods for background subtraction. The problem is that they are quite computationally expensive and less suitable for running on the Raspberry Pi ‚Äî but they are tend to do a better job at background subtraction. I plan on writing a blog post on the more advanced methods of background subtraction built into OpenCV later this year, so be sure to keep an eye on the blog!
        Reply
            Miraj February 13, 2016 at 9:55 am #

            Oh that makes sense‚Äîthanks for the info.

            Quick question regarding the camera.capture_continuous function‚Äîhow is that called? Is that just capturing the current frame present in the video capture, or does it build up a backlog / buffer of frames not yet processed yet (capturing each frame according to the frame rate)?

            Thanks!
            Reply
                Adrian Rosebrock February 13, 2016 at 11:29 am #

                It‚Äôs capturing the current frame. If you need a backlog/buffer, you should use the Queue Python data-structure.
