    David November 22, 2016 at 6:15 am #

    Dear Adrian,
    Thanks a lot for your great tutorials! I‚Äôm a beginner with Python and OpenCV, but nevertheless it made sense and was explained beautifully.
    I was able to combine your previous post (Basic motion detection and tracking with Python and OpenCV) and this one to make it run properly under Windows 7 with Python 3.5.2. The averaging have removed the noise, but the problem I‚Äôm now facing is that in case that an object moved in the frame, and then stopped moving, the system will go back to ‚Äúunoccupied‚Äù state, even though the object (i.e. person stealing my beer) is still in the room. How would you suggest solving that issue?
    Thanks
    Reply
        Adrian Rosebrock November 22, 2016 at 12:29 pm #

        If an object stops moving, then by definition, no motion is occurring. If you want to maintain a larger history of motion you‚Äôll want to play with the weight parameter to cv2.accumulateWeighted(gray, avg, 0.5) . In this case it‚Äôs 0.5, but you can decrease the value to have the ‚Äúhistory‚Äù of motion last longer.

        Alternatively, once you‚Äôve detected motion you can apply methods such as CamShift and correlation filters to continue to track the object (even if it stops moving).
        Reply
    amri yahya November 25, 2016 at 10:12 pm #

